5mw.title: Greatest common divisor
5mw.clickbait: The greatest common divisor of two natural numbers is… the largest number which is a divisor of both. The clue is in the name, really.
5mw.text:
[summary: The greatest common divisor of two [45h natural numbers] is the largest number which divides both of them.]

There are two ways to define the **greatest common divisor** (also known as **greatest common factor**, or **highest common factor**), both equivalent.

The first definition is as the name suggests: the GCD of $a$ and $b$ is the largest number which divides both $a$ and $b$.

The second definition is the more "mathematical", because it generalises to arbitrary [3gq rings] rather than just [55j ordered rings].
The GCD of $a$ and $b$ is the number $c$ such that $c \mid a$, $c \mid b$, and whenever $d \mid a$ and $d \mid b$, we have $d \mid c$.
(That is, it is the maximal element of the [-3rb] that consists of the divisors of $a$ and $b$, ordered by division.)
